questionRound.0.question.9.answer: Game theory can hurt my brain sometimes because I like to think of all the possibilities that people could make and how it will affect the consequences or the actions of others. And one person needs to make the decision before others start being affected by a decision (and you don't know if someone is going to play it smart or play it big... so to me  it's a guessing game of what people will do). For this study  I decided to not think of the chain of actions from each scenario (e.g. looking at if Green first chooses  what will happen... and then looking at if Red first choose  what will happen... and then looking at if Blue first choose  what will happen). I only thought of how the person who would have the immediate impact would do. For example  on Display 3  if I am Orange  I would look at the Red table because Red's decision affects my payoff. I assume that Red would choose Y_R because it has the highest payoff of 25. Since I assume Red will choose Y_R  I would then compare X_O and X_Y using the Y_R column in my Orange payoff box. I would choose Y_O because it has a higher payoff than X_O w/ Y_R. This worked for the most part. I only had it not work for 2-3 matches. I wish I had more time to go and think about all the possibilities that people could take.

In the beginning  I based my decisions off of the greed of others and what they would choose. Very quickly  however  I saw that there was a pattern in which one color would have an obvious choice  where they would earn more from either choice from one option then they would another. I then followed that other people would use these same deductions to allow me to guess which choices they would choose and for me to maximize my output from their choices. It worked very well except for one outlier at the very beginning in which I got 4  where somebody hadn't followed the train of thought.

In every round there was usually one player who did not have to worry about the decisions of the other players to make the most beneficial choice (ie choosing Xo would have given him the best outcome regardless of what any other player chose). The other players all had one good outcome and one not so good outcome depending on the choice of another person. I started with the "obvious choice" of the person who did not have to worry about the other choices  and predicted the choices of the other members based on the "obvious choice" until I got to my decision.
Just figure out the group who will definitely chose the higher option Getting which option they must choose  then I guess one group by another until my group.

I logically assumed what the other players would choose in order to increase their total  and took this into account when choosing my own. This meant starting from the Green player who had an obvious choice of an option which would be have to give them a higher total  and working back from that to my choice.

I actually looked at the highest numbers on my screen first and then I looked at the quantities from whoever rested upon me getting that amount whether I chose X or Y and then by those larger numbers from the other person  whether they were X or Y I made my decisions.

If I had high numbers along a row in both columns  then I would pick that row as it was statistically my best chance to win the most. Otherwise  if each row had one high number and one low number  I would look and see what the person who would determine my amount had. If he had a situation with high numbers along a row  I would assume he would pick that row  and pick my row accordingly.

Firstly  i check whether one of the two pairs of payoff depend on my choice is strictly larger than the other. If so  I just pick the larger one. If not  I continue to check the next guy's payoff. If he has the situation  I assume he will choose as me so that I can pick the higher payoff of myself depend on his move. If it is still not the case  I move on to the third guy as check as above to backward to my decision.

It seemed that each game only had 1 square where one row was definitley a better choice than the other. I found that square and assumed that the person who's square that was would choose that row. With that information  I followed the trail back to my own square using the rows taht each individual would choose if they also knew what I knew about the very square I mentioned. Knowing what the person "in front of me" would choose  I chose the most valuable responce for myself.
I looked at the farthest player right  and determined the other players' moves from that point on.

I attempted to select the best possible option based on the values that were given to me. For example  if the two top rows had the two highest numbers out of the four I could select I would select the option that would give me one of those two numbers and disregarded what the other individual could have selected. Also  I anticipated whatever patterns this study attempted to form as well as transition out of throughout the experiment. I made sure I made note of some of the patterns other colors had as well.

There is always one player who has a choice benefiting him/her more no matter what other players choose. Suppose all players are rational  from his choice  I can predict what the player who rely on the first player's choice will choose. And do this in sequence  I can finally know what the player I rely on will choose  and when I know my chioce --- Suppose all players know this logic and are rational.
